  "chunk_index": 13,
  "summary": "After speaking with Frank Carter and Gladys Neville, Hercule Poirot contacts Inspector Japp to discuss the mysterious telegram sent to Miss Neville. Poirot suspects a conspiracy, noting that the telegram was cleverly sent from Ritching Bourn to mimic Ritching, Somerset. He suggests the telegram may have been a timed prank intended to lure Miss Neville away from the clinic on the day Molly was scheduled to give an injection, potentially causing a fatal mistake in her absence. Japp maintains that the case regarding the death of Mr. Ambrosio is clear, as the fatal substance was injected rather than ingested, and notes that the investigation into the missing Sylvia continues.\n\nLater, Poirot discusses the death of his own dentist, Mr. Morley, with his butler, George. While the public believes Morley committed suicide, Poirot considers murder. He reviews a list of potential suspects who were in the house: a cook, a maid, Morley's sister (the heir to his estate), a partner, a pageboy, and a deceased Greek gentleman. George suggests the Greek gentleman and Morley may have intended to kill each other. Poirot expands his list to include an American gentleman seen in the waiting room who was not seen leaving, and Frank Carter, who arrived after 12:00. Poirot notes that if an American named Mr. Amberloz were the killer, the crime occurred between 12:05 and 12:20; otherwise, it occurred after 12:25. He realizes he has omitted Mr. Barnes from his list of people present during the incident. Finally, Jane Olivia, the great-niece of Alistair Brent, calls Poirot to request that he visit Gothic Hall to discuss a matter with her.",
